{"title_page": "Koopalings", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox character\n|color      = #EC7365\n|name       = Koopalings\n|image      = Koopalings - New Super Mario Bros U.png\n|caption    = Promotional artwork for ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U]]'' showing the seven Koopalings. From left to right: Lemmy, Wendy, Morton, Larry, Iggy, Ludwig, and Roy.\n|series     = [[Mario (franchise)|Mario]]\n|first  = ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' (1988)\n|voice = [[#Voice actors and namesakes|See below]]\n|portrayer  = [[Fisher Stevens]] as Iggy\n([[Super Mario Bros (film)|Super Mario Bros]])\n}}\nThe {{Nihongo|'''Koopalings'''|\u30b3\u30af\u30c3\u30d1|Kokuppa}} (also known as {{Nihongo|'''Bowser's minions'''|\u30af\u30c3\u30d1\u306e\u624b\u4e0b|Kuppa no Teshita}} in Japan and Europe or {{Nihongo|'''7 Bowser Team'''|\u30af\u30c3\u30d17\u4eba\u8846|Kuppa Shichi Ninsh\u016b}} in Japan) are a fictional group of seven childlike characters in the [[Mario (franchise)|''Mario'']] [[video game franchise]] by [[Nintendo]]. Their individual names are [[Larry Koopa]], [[Roy Koopa]], [[Lemmy Koopa]], [[Wendy O. Koopa]], [[Iggy Koopa]], [[Morton Koopa]], and [[Ludwig von Koopa]]. Originally depicted as the children of the series antagonist [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]], they first appeared as [[boss (video games)|boss character]]s in the 1988 game ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]''. They have since appeared in subsequent ''[[Super Mario]]'' games and [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] ''Mario'' titles.\n\nThey have made several appearances in other media, most notably in the animated series ''[[The Adventures of Super Mario Bros. 3]]'', which featured entirely different names for the Koopalings due to them not having official names at the time of its production phase.\n\n==Concept and creation==\nThe Koopalings first appeared on a sketch by [[Yoichi Kotabe]] and [[Takashi Tezuka]] whose aim was finding a definitive redesign of Bowser for the [[Family Computer Disk System]] version of ''[[Super Mario Bros.: The Lost Levels]]''.<ref>As noted in the caption of [https://www.mariowiki.com/images/f/f7/Bowser_Koopalings_sketch.png the sketch found on page 65 of the ''Official Nintendo Guidebook'' of ''Super Mario Collection'']. The text says:''At first Bowser's appearance was not entirely settled. In order to get to this version of the sketch, Kotabe and Tezuka collaborated multiple times.'' The page of the guide itself is dedicated to ''Super Mario Bros. 2'', the Japanese name of ''[[Super Mario Bros.: The Lost Levels]]''.</ref> Most of the Koopalings are distinguished by their wild [[punk fashion|punk]] hairstyles. The first names of the Koopalings would later be adapted for the Japanese version of ''[[Super Mario World]]'', which was released a few months after the North American release of ''Super Mario Bros. 3''. However, the Koopalings received a set of different names in the [[DIC Entertainment|DiC]]-produced ''[[The Adventures of Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' animated series, as they were still unnamed when the show was in production.\n\nThe Koopalings were originally created to be Bowser's children, as it was mentioned in Japanese ''Super Mario Bros. 3'' instruction books as well as early materials.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ov8A5tz8MU0 |title=Super Mario Bros. 3 \u2013 Famimaga Sept. 1988 Early Beta Footage |via=YouTube |accessdate=September 23, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/clv/manuals/ja/pdf/CLV-P-HAACJ.pdf |title=Original Japanese manual of ''Super Mario Bros. 3''. |publisher= Nintendo Co., Ltd. |accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref> Subsequent official sources also confirmed that they were his offspring.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendo.co.uk/Games/NES/Super-Mario-Bros-3-279558.html |title=''Super Mario Bros. 3'' page on Nintendo UK's site. |publisher= Nintendo UK |accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>\"Bowser, King of the Koopas, and his evil offspring have invaded yet another kingdom. The Koopalings have seized the Kingdom's precious crystals. It's up to you, armed with your trusty Nintendo Scope, to ride Yoshi to the rescue!\", back of the box of the North American and PAL versions of ''[[Yoshi's Safari]]''.</ref> This portrayal was generally accepted by both Japanese and western gamers and media for a long time. Since [[Bowser Jr.]] was introduced and the Koopalings went on a six-year hiatus after ''[[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga]]'' only to return referred to as ''Bowser's minions'' in the Japanese and European versions of ''[[New Super Mario Bros. Wii]]'', there has been confusion on whether the Koopalings were still considered Bowser's children or not, with Shigeru Miyamoto confirming during an interview in 2012 that \"our current story is that the seven Koopalings are not Bowser's children. Bowser's only child is Bowser Jr., and we do not know who the mother is.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2012/09/24/miyamoto-tezuka-interview.aspx |title=Mario's Creators Answer Burning Questions About The Series |publisher=Game Informer |accessdate=December 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130123161706/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2012/09/24/miyamoto-tezuka-interview.aspx |archive-date=January 23, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> According to the North American website for ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U]]'', the Koopalings are also siblings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsupermariobrosu.nintendo.com/characters/#/koopalings |title=New Super Mario Bros. U Character Profile: Koopalings |publisher=Nintendo |accessdate=December 18, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\n===''Super Mario'' series===\nThe Koopalings appear in six games in the [[Super Mario (series)|''Super Mario'' series]]. In each game, the Koopalings each serve as the main [[Boss (video gaming)|boss character]] fought by the player at the end of each individual region in the game's setting. Their first appearance was ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'', released in 1988 for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]], where they each conquer one of seven kingdoms in the Mushroom World by stealing its king's magical [[wand]] and using it to transform him into an animal, or in one case, plant.<ref name=\"smb3 manual\">{{cite book | title=Super Mario Bros. 3 | publisher=[[Nintendo]] | location=USA | year=1990}}</ref>{{rp|5}} The Koopalings then appeared in the 1990 [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]] game ''[[Super Mario World]]'', which immediately follows the events of ''Super Mario Bros. 3'', holding [[Yoshi]]s captive in eggs at each of their respective castles in Dinosaur Land.<ref>{{cite book | title=Super Mario World | publisher=[[Nintendo]] | location=USA | year=1991}}</ref>{{rp|19}}\n\nThe Koopalings were absent from subsequent ''Super Mario'' games until the release of ''[[New Super Mario Bros. Wii]]'' for the [[Wii]] in 2009,<ref name=\"revenge\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/06/29/revenge-of-the-koopalings-stars-icons |title=Revenge of the Koopalings: Stars Icons |author=Thomas, Lucas M. |date=June 29, 2009 |accessdate=February 16, 2014 |publisher=[[IGN]]}}</ref> which marks their [[3D computer graphics|3D]] debut, and most of them having slight design changes from their original appearances. They then appeared in ''[[New Super Mario Bros. 2]]'' for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] and ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U]]'' for the [[Wii U]] along with its [[Downloadable content|DLC]] ''[[New Super Luigi U]]'', both released in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/new-super-luigi-u-review/1900-6410778/|title=New Super Luigi U Review|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref> They also appeared in ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U Deluxe]]''. All seven will appear in the version 3.0 update of ''[[Super Mario Maker 2]]'', each with their own attack style. They cannot be used in the ''[[Super Mario 3D World]]'' theme, however.\n\n===Spin-off games===\nThe Koopalings have appeared as [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]] characters in the [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] ''[[Mario (franchise)|Mario]]'' games ''[[Yoshi's Safari]]'', ''[[Mario Is Missing!]]'', and ''[[Hotel Mario]]'', released from 1992 to 1994 on various platforms. They then appeared in the 2003 [[Game Boy Advance]] video game ''[[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga]]'' and its [[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga + Bowser's Minions|3DS remake]],<ref name=\"revenge\"/> where they served as bosses in [[Super Mario (series)|Bowser's Castle]], the last area of the game. They were supposed to be included in the [[Nintendo DS]] game ''[[Super Princess Peach]]'' but were cut for unknown reason, and only leftover [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]] remain in the game. In ''[[Mario Kart 8]]'' for the [[Wii U]] in 2014, the Koopalings made their debut as [[Player character|playable characters]] for the first time. They also then reappeared in ''[[Mario Kart 8 Deluxe]]'' for the [[Nintendo Switch]] and in ''[[Mario Kart Tour]]'' on mobile.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/_Wd1rwaLzjbhkN9T0xfCiMzKcliGysyo |date=February 13, 2014 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |title=Little Mac Joins the Super Smash Bros. Cast; Mario Kart 8 Launches May 30 with Koopalings |accessdate=February 16, 2014}}</ref> In ''[[Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U]]'' and ''[[Super Smash Bros Ultimate]]'', each of [[Bowser Jr.]]'s seven alternate costumes replace him with one of the Koopalings, with each one fighting from atop the Junior Clown Car.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/people-are-starting-to-unlock-secret-smash-bros-charact-1633365911|title=People Are Starting to Unlock Secret Smash Bros. Characters [Update]|first=Patricia|last=Hernandez}}</ref> They appear once again in ''[[Mario & Luigi: Paper Jam]]'', released in 2015 for the [[Nintendo 3DS]], in which they all once again carry out roles as bosses. In ''[[Paper Mario: Color Splash]]'', the Koopalings appear as bosses for the first time in a ''[[Paper Mario series|Paper Mario]]'' game.{{Citation needed|date=February 2017}} The Koopalings also appeared in ''[[Mario & Luigi: Bowser's Inside Story + Bowser Jr.'s Journey]]'' as playable characters in Bowser Jr.'s Journey mode. Neither of them appear in the ''[[Mario Party]]'' or ''[[Mario Golf]]'' series but they may become playable characters for the first time soon after.\n\n===In other media===\n[[File:SMB3-TV-Koopalings.jpg|thumb|The Koopalings as they appear in ''[[The Adventures of Super Mario Bros. 3]]'']]\nThe Koopalings made their first animated appearance in the ''[[Amada Anime Series: Super Mario Bros.]]'' [[original video animation|OVA]] series, released in 1989. In the animated cartoon series ''[[The Adventures of Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' produced by [[DIC Entertainment]], the '''Koopa Kids''' were given different names based on their given personalities. Their ages are also changed. From oldest to youngest, they are '''Bully Koopa''' (Roy), '''Big Mouth Koopa''' (Morton), '''Kooky Von Koopa''' (Ludwig), '''Cheatsy Koopa''' (Larry), '''Kootie Pie Koopa''' (Wendy), and '''Hip and Hop Koopa''' (Lemmy and Iggy respectively). After this, they appear in another animated cartoon series ''[[Super Mario World (TV series)|Super Mario World]]'' with the same names, though they more closely resemble their portrayals in the video games. Aside from their names and personalities, they look slightly different and serve their father King Koopa (as Bowser was called in the series) differently compared to their video game counterparts. Instead of their subordinate role, they act directly as his children, and do things such as seek his attention, and even plot against him. They would also appear in the [[Nintendo Adventure Books]] and comic books, wherein they use their official names and designs closer to the games.{{cn|date=September 2017}}\n{{br}}\n==Voice actors and namesakes==\nMost of the Koopalings were named after celebrities\u2014mainly famous musicians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/how-a-mario-character-was-named-after-motorheads-lemmy-1750180427|title=How A Mario Character Was Named After Motorhead's Lemmy|first=Patrick|last=Klepek}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Vintage Games: An Insider Look at the History of Grand Theft Auto, Super Mario, and the Most Influential Games of All Time|last1=Loguidice|first1=Bill|last2=Barton|first2=Matt|publisher=[[CRC Press]]|year=2012|isbn=9781136137587|page=282|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mKF5AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA326}}</ref> Each Koopaling has had four or five voice actors in different media.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2| Name !! rowspan=2|Amada Anime series (1989) !! rowspan=2|DiC animated series (1990\u20131991) !! rowspan=2|''[[Mario Is Missing!]]'' (DOS, 1992) !! colspan=2|Video games (2009\u2013present) !! rowspan=2|Named after\n|-\n! <small>2009\u20132013,<br>2014\u20132019</small>{{refn|group=note|According to voice actor Mike Vaughn (Ludwig and Iggy), only one recording session was done in October of 2009 for ''New Super Mario Bros. Wii'', and those same audio files have been reused in several future titles that have featured the Koopalings since, the most recent being ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U|New Super Mario Bros. U Deluxe]]''. Vaughn has publicly called this action a theft by Nintendo as the usage release signed by both parties prohibited Nintendo from using those files in advertisements or promotions. While not specifically restricting usage in future games, Vaughn asked, \"Who in their right mind would have thought that a major game producer would use the same audio in future titles? Seems like a great way to make really bad, repetitive games to me.\"<ref>[http://www.blogtalkradio.com/cloverleafradio/2013/12/22/cloverleaf-radio-presents-actor-mike-vaughn-super-mario-bros Cloverleaf Radio Presents: Actor Mike Vaughn \"Super Mario Bros.\"!!]. Blog Talk Radio (January 2014). Retrieved November 18, 2014.</ref> Eventually, new voice actors were hired to record the Koopalings for ''Mario Kart 8'', with the exception of Roy, who retained his original voice actor.}} !! <small>2014\u2013present</small>\n|-\n| Larry Koopa || [[Masaharu Sat\u014d]] || James Rankin || Rob Wallace || rowspan=3|[[Lani Minella]] || Michelle Hippe || [[Larry Mullen Jr.|Larry Mullen]]\n|-\n| Morton Koopa Jr. || rowspan=2|[[Miyako End\u014d]] || Gordon Masten || {{N/a|Not used in final game}} || David Cooke || [[Morton Downey Jr.]]\n|-\n| Wendy O. Koopa || [[Tabitha St. Germain|Paulina Gillis]] || Kathy Fitzgerald || Ashley Flannegan || [[Wendy O. Williams]]\n|-\n| Iggy Koopa || Masaharu Sat\u014d || [[Tara Strong|Tara Charendoff]] || Rob Wallace || Mike Vaughn || Ryan Higgins || [[Iggy Pop]]\n|-\n| Roy Koopa || rowspan=3|[[Naoki Tatsuta]] || [[Dan Hennessey]]  || Bruce Sandig || colspan=2|Dan Falcone || [[Roy Orbison]]\n|-\n| Lemmy Koopa || Tara Charendoff || {{N/a|Not used in final game}} || Lani Minella || Carlee McManus || [[Lemmy|Lemmy Kilmister]]\n|-\n| Ludwig von Koopa || [[Michael Stark]] || Rob Wallace || Mike Vaughn || David J. Goldfarb || [[Ludwig van Beethoven]]\n|}\n\n==Reception==\nSince their appearance in ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'', the Koopalings have had mostly positive reception, being referred to by [[Nintendo]] as common knowledge of the ''Mario'' series due to their appearance in ''Super Mario Bros. 3''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ugo.com/games/super-mario-brothers-3-on-the-virtual-console |title=Super Mario Brothers 3 on the Virtual Console |publisher=UGO.com |date=November 5, 2007 |accessdate=August 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615033521/http://www.ugo.com/games/super-mario-brothers-3-on-the-virtual-console |archivedate=June 15, 2011  }}</ref> Their popularity amongst fans led to them being reused for the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]] sequel, ''[[Super Mario World]]''. [[Nintendo Power]] listed each Koopaling as one of the reasons to love Nintendo, describing them as some of Nintendo's most beloved villains. They cited their eccentric designs for the quality of their personalities.<ref>{{cite book |title=[[Nintendo Power]] 250th issue! |year=2010 |publisher=[[Future US]] |location=[[South San Francisco, California]] |page=60 }}</ref> The Koopalings were named the 19th best Mario villains by [[GameDaily]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Chris Buffa |url=http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/top-25-mario-enemies/?page=7&cp=2 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081207204712/http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/top-25-mario-enemies/?page=7&cp=2 |archivedate=December 7, 2008 |title=Gallery and Images |publisher=GameDaily |date=October 3, 2008 |accessdate=August 5, 2010}}</ref> [[GamesRadar]] editor Henry Gilbert described the battle at the end of each world in ''Super Mario Bros. 3'' as a \"special affair\"; he also praised them for adding variety to the series compared to ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'', which featured Bowser as the last boss of each castle.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/f/super-mario-bros-3-20-years-later/a-2010021210412332034/p-2/c-1?newest |title=Super Mario Bros 3: 20 years later |publisher=GamesRadar |accessdate=August 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615200618/http://www.gamesradar.com/f/super-mario-bros-3-20-years-later/a-2010021210412332034/p-2/c-1?newest |archivedate=June 15, 2011  }}</ref> [[IGN]] editor Lucas M. Thomas echoed these sentiments, stating that the Koopalings brought their own looks, mannerisms, and methods of attack. Specifically, he described the battle with Lemmy Koopa in ''Super Mario Bros. 3'' as unique and memorable, while also describing Ludwig von Koopa's battle in ''[[Super Mario World]]'' as distinct from the others.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thomas |first=Lucas M. |url=http://stars.ign.com/articles/998/998186p1.html |title=Revenge of the Koopalings: Stars Icons \u2013 Stars Feature at IGN |publisher=Stars.ign.com |date=June 29, 2009 |accessdate=August 5, 2010}}</ref> In another article he listed the Koopalings as one of the characters he wants in ''[[Mario Kart 7]]'', especially Wendy O. Koopa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.ds.ign.com/articles/121/1213061p1.html|title=Predicting Mario Kart 7's Final Characters|publisher=IGN|first=Lucas M.|last=Thomas|accessdate=September 18, 2016 }}</ref> Fellow IGN editor Jesse Schedeen featured the Koopalings in the \"Big Boss of the Day\" feature, describing them as popular bosses in video games.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schedeen |first=Jesse |url=http://stars.ign.com/articles/105/1052937p1.html |title=Big Boss of the Day: The Koopa Kids \u2013 Stars Feature at IGN |publisher=Stars.ign.com |date=December 7, 2009 |accessdate=August 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Joystiq]] editor James Ransom-Wiley called their reappearance in ''[[New Super Mario Bros. Wii]]'' a welcome addition, stating that it should boost the quality of the bosses.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ransom |first=James |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2006/03/09/koopalings-to-return-in-new-super-mario-bros-yoshi-on-the-side/ |title=Koopalings to return in New Super Mario Bros., Yoshi on the sideline |publisher=Joystiq |date=March 9, 2006 |accessdate=August 5, 2010}}</ref> Fellow Joystiq editor JC Fletcher described them as a draw for ''New Super Mario Bros. Wii'' for some fans, also praising the three-dimensional designs of the Koopalings.<ref>{{cite web|author=JC Fletcher on |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2009/10/26/new-super-character-art-from-new-super-mario-bros-wii/ |title=New, super character art from New Super Mario Bros. Wii |publisher=Joystiq |date=October 26, 2009 |accessdate=August 5, 2010}}</ref> During an interview with ''[[Super Mario Galaxy]]'' director [[Yoshiaki Koizumi]], [[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] noted that they were hoping for the Koopalings to return in it.<ref name=\"egm\">{{cite web |url=http://www.1up.com/features/super-mario-galaxy-afterthoughts |title=Super Mario Galaxy Afterthoughts from |publisher=1UP.com |date=February 19, 2008 |accessdate=August 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111129052432/http://www.1up.com/features/super-mario-galaxy-afterthoughts |archivedate=November 29, 2011  }}</ref> [[Destructoid]] editor Conrad Zimmerman stated that the Koopalings were his favorite characters from ''Super Mario Bros. 3'', and added that with regard to the musical references in the Koopalings' names, he doubted that anything similar would be seen in this day and age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/see-larry-koopa-strut-his-stuff-once-more-137093.phtml |title=See Larry Koopa strut his stuff once more |publisher=Destructoid |accessdate=August 5, 2010}}</ref> [[GameSpy]] editor Ryan Scott listed the Koopalings as one of the reasons why ''Super Mario Bros. 3'' and ''Super Mario World'' were quality video games.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespy.com/articles/105/1057201p2.html |title=Game of the Year 2009: Our Personal Picks \u2013 Page 2 |publisher=GameSpy |accessdate=August 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226020637/http://www.gamespy.com/articles/105/1057201p2.html |archivedate=December 26, 2009  }}</ref> He also praised ''New Super Mario Bros. Wii'' for the inclusion of the Koopalings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wii.gamespy.com/wii/super-mario-wii-2/991378p1.html |title=GameSpy: E3 2009: New Super Mario Bros. Wii Hands-on \u2013 Page 1 |publisher=Wii.gamespy.com |accessdate=August 5, 2010}}</ref> The GameSpy staff listed the Koopalings as some of their favorite bosses, stating that they have much more charm than their \"dopey successor\", Bowser Jr.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://xbox360.gamespy.com/articles/103/1036217p1.html |title=GameSpy: GameSpy's Favorite Videogame Bosses \u2013 Page 1 |publisher=Xbox360.gamespy.com |accessdate=August 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808171233/http://xbox360.gamespy.com/articles/103/1036217p1.html |archivedate=August 8, 2010  }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Wikipedia books|Mario franchise characters}}\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Mario franchise}}\n{{Super Smash Bros. series}}\n\n[[Category:Anthropomorphic characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Child characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional criminals in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional kidnappers]]\n[[Category:Fictional turtles]]\n[[Category:Mario enemies]]\n[[Category:Super Smash Bros. fighters]]\n[[Category:Mario characters]]\n[[Category:Nintendo antagonists]]\n[[Category:Fictional septets]]\n[[Category:Video game bosses]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 1988]]\n[[Category:Video game nobility]]\n[[Category:Fictional henchmen in video games]]\n[[Category:Video game characters who use magic]]\n[[Category:Video game characters with fire or heat abilities]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox character\n|color      = #EC7365\n|name       = Koopalings\n|image      = Koopalings - New Super Mario Bros U.png\n|caption    = Promotional artwork for ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U]]'' showing the seven Koopalings. From left to right: Lemmy, Wendy, Morton, Larry, Iggy, Ludwig, and Roy.\n|series     = [[Mario (franchise)|Mario]]\n|first  = ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' (1988)\n|voice = [[#Voice actors and namesakes|See below]]\n|portrayer  = [[Fisher Stevens]] as Iggy\n([[Super Mario Bros (film)|Super Mario Bros]])\n}}\nThe {{Nihongo|'''Koopalings'''|\u30b3\u30af\u30c3\u30d1|Kokuppa}} (also known as {{Nihongo|'''Bowser's minions'''|\u30af\u30c3\u30d1\u306e\u624b\u4e0b|Kuppa no Teshita}} in Japan and Europe or {{Nihongo|'''7 Bowser Team'''|\u30af\u30c3\u30d17\u4eba\u8846|Kuppa Shichi Ninsh\u016b}} in Japan) are a fictional group of seven childlike characters in the [[Mario (franchise)|''Mario'']] [[video game franchise]] by [[Nintendo]]. Their individual names are [[Larry Koopa]], [[Roy Koopa]], [[Lemmy Koopa]], [[Wendy O. Koopa]], [[Iggy Koopa]], [[Morton Koopa]], and [[Ludwig von Koopa]]. Originally depicted as the children of the series antagonist [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]], they first appeared as [[boss (video games)|boss character]]s in the 1988 game ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]''. They have since appeared in subsequent ''[[Super Mario]]'' games and [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] ''Mario'' titles.\n\nThey have made several appearances in other media, most notably in the animated series ''[[The Adventures of Super Mario Bros. 3]]'', which featured entirely different names for the Koopalings due to them not having official names at the time of its production phase.\n\n==Concept and creation==\nThe Koopalings first appeared on a sketch by [[Yoichi Kotabe]] and [[Takashi Tezuka]] whose aim was finding a definitive redesign of Bowser for the [[Family Computer Disk System]] version of ''[[Super Mario Bros.: The Lost Levels]]''.<ref>As noted in the caption of [https://www.mariowiki.com/images/f/f7/Bowser_Koopalings_sketch.png the sketch found on page 65 of the ''Official Nintendo Guidebook'' of ''Super Mario Collection'']. The text says:''At first Bowser's appearance was not entirely settled. In order to get to this version of the sketch, Kotabe and Tezuka collaborated multiple times.'' The page of the guide itself is dedicated to ''Super Mario Bros. 2'', the Japanese name of ''[[Super Mario Bros.: The Lost Levels]]''.</ref> Most of the Koopalings are distinguished by their wild [[punk fashion|punk]] hairstyles. The first names of the Koopalings would later be adapted for the Japanese version of ''[[Super Mario World]]'', which was released a few months after the North American release of ''Super Mario Bros. 3''. However, the Koopalings received a set of different names in the [[DIC Entertainment|DiC]]-produced ''[[The Adventures of Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' animated series, as they were still unnamed when the show was in production.\n\nThe Koopalings were originally created to be Bowser's children, as it was mentioned in Japanese ''Super Mario Bros. 3'' instruction books as well as early materials.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ov8A5tz8MU0 |title=Super Mario Bros. 3 \u2013 Famimaga Sept. 1988 Early Beta Footage |via=YouTube |accessdate=September 23, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/clv/manuals/ja/pdf/CLV-P-HAACJ.pdf |title=Original Japanese manual of ''Super Mario Bros. 3''. |publisher= Nintendo Co., Ltd. |accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref> Subsequent official sources also confirmed that they were his offspring.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendo.co.uk/Games/NES/Super-Mario-Bros-3-279558.html |title=''Super Mario Bros. 3'' page on Nintendo UK's site. |publisher= Nintendo UK |accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>\"Bowser, King of the Koopas, and his evil offspring have invaded yet another kingdom. The Koopalings have seized the Kingdom's precious crystals. It's up to you, armed with your trusty Nintendo Scope, to ride Yoshi to the rescue!\", back of the box of the North American and PAL versions of ''[[Yoshi's Safari]]''.</ref> This portrayal was generally accepted by both Japanese and western gamers and media for a long time. Since [[Bowser Jr.]] was introduced and the Koopalings went on a six-year hiatus after ''[[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga]]'' only to return referred to as ''Bowser's minions'' in the Japanese and European versions of ''[[New Super Mario Bros. Wii]]'', there has been confusion on whether the Koopalings were still considered Bowser's children or not, with Shigeru Miyamoto confirming during an interview in 2012 that \"our current story is that the seven Koopalings are not Bowser's children. Bowser's only child is Bowser Jr., and we do not know who the mother is.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2012/09/24/miyamoto-tezuka-interview.aspx |title=Mario's Creators Answer Burning Questions About The Series |publisher=Game Informer |accessdate=December 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130123161706/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2012/09/24/miyamoto-tezuka-interview.aspx |archive-date=January 23, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> According to the North American website for ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U]]'', the Koopalings are also siblings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsupermariobrosu.nintendo.com/characters/#/koopalings |title=New Super Mario Bros. U Character Profile: Koopalings |publisher=Nintendo |accessdate=December 18, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\n===''Super Mario'' series===\nThe Koopalings appear in five games in the [[Super Mario (series)|''Super Mario'' series]]. In each game, the Koopalings each serve as the main [[Boss (video gaming)|boss character]] fought by the player at the end of each individual region in the game's setting. Their first appearance was ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'', released in 1988 for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]], where they each conquer one of seven kingdoms in the Mushroom World by stealing its king's magical [[wand]] and using it to transform him into an animal, or in one case, plant.<ref name=\"smb3 manual\">{{cite book | title=Super Mario Bros. 3 | publisher=[[Nintendo]] | location=USA | year=1990}}</ref>{{rp|5}} The Koopalings then appeared in the 1990 [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]] game ''[[Super Mario World]]'', which immediately follows the events of ''Super Mario Bros. 3'', holding [[Yoshi]]s captive in eggs at each of their respective castles in Dinosaur Land.<ref>{{cite book | title=Super Mario World | publisher=[[Nintendo]] | location=USA | year=1991}}</ref>{{rp|19}}\n\nThe Koopalings were absent from subsequent ''Super Mario'' games until the release of ''[[New Super Mario Bros. Wii]]'' for the [[Wii]] in 2009,<ref name=\"revenge\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/06/29/revenge-of-the-koopalings-stars-icons |title=Revenge of the Koopalings: Stars Icons |author=Thomas, Lucas M. |date=June 29, 2009 |accessdate=February 16, 2014 |publisher=[[IGN]]}}</ref> which marks their [[3D computer graphics|3D]] debut, and most of them having slight design changes from their original appearances. They then appeared in ''[[New Super Mario Bros. 2]]'' for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] and ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U]]'' for the [[Wii U]] along with its [[Downloadable content|DLC]] ''[[New Super Luigi U]]'', both released in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/new-super-luigi-u-review/1900-6410778/|title=New Super Luigi U Review|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref> They also appeared in ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U Deluxe]]''. All seven will appear in the version 3.0 update of ''[[Super Mario Maker 2]]'', each with their own attack style. They cannot be used in the ''[[Super Mario 3D World]]'' theme, however.\n\n===Spin-off games===\nThe Koopalings have appeared as [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]] characters in the [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] ''[[Mario (franchise)|Mario]]'' games ''[[Yoshi's Safari]]'', ''[[Mario Is Missing!]]'', and ''[[Hotel Mario]]'', released from 1992 to 1994 on various platforms. They then appeared in the 2003 [[Game Boy Advance]] video game ''[[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga]]'' and its [[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga + Bowser's Minions|3DS remake]],<ref name=\"revenge\"/> where they served as bosses in [[Super Mario (series)|Bowser's Castle]], the last area of the game. They were supposed to be included in the [[Nintendo DS]] game ''[[Super Princess Peach]]'' but were cut for unknown reason, and only leftover [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]] remain in the game. In ''[[Mario Kart 8]]'' for the [[Wii U]] in 2014, the Koopalings made their debut as [[Player character|playable characters]] for the first time. They also then reappeared in ''[[Mario Kart 8 Deluxe]]'' for the [[Nintendo Switch]] and in ''[[Mario Kart Tour]]'' on mobile.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/_Wd1rwaLzjbhkN9T0xfCiMzKcliGysyo |date=February 13, 2014 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |title=Little Mac Joins the Super Smash Bros. Cast; Mario Kart 8 Launches May 30 with Koopalings |accessdate=February 16, 2014}}</ref> In ''[[Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U]]'' and ''[[Super Smash Bros Ultimate]]'', each of [[Bowser Jr.]]'s seven alternate costumes replace him with one of the Koopalings, with each one fighting from atop the Junior Clown Car.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/people-are-starting-to-unlock-secret-smash-bros-charact-1633365911|title=People Are Starting to Unlock Secret Smash Bros. Characters [Update]|first=Patricia|last=Hernandez}}</ref> They appear once again in ''[[Mario & Luigi: Paper Jam]]'', released in 2015 for the [[Nintendo 3DS]], in which they all once again carry out roles as bosses. In ''[[Paper Mario: Color Splash]]'', the Koopalings appear as bosses for the first time in a ''[[Paper Mario series|Paper Mario]]'' game.{{Citation needed|date=February 2017}} The Koopalings also appeared in ''[[Mario & Luigi: Bowser's Inside Story + Bowser Jr.'s Journey]]'' as playable characters in Bowser Jr.'s Journey mode. Neither of them appear in the ''[[Mario Party]]'' or ''[[Mario Golf]]'' series but they may become playable characters for the first time soon after.\n\n===In other media===\n[[File:SMB3-TV-Koopalings.jpg|thumb|The Koopalings as they appear in ''[[The Adventures of Super Mario Bros. 3]]'']]\nThe Koopalings made their first animated appearance in the ''[[Amada Anime Series: Super Mario Bros.]]'' [[original video animation|OVA]] series, released in 1989. In the animated cartoon series ''[[The Adventures of Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' produced by [[DIC Entertainment]], the '''Koopa Kids''' were given different names based on their given personalities. Their ages are also changed. From oldest to youngest, they are '''Bully Koopa''' (Roy), '''Big Mouth Koopa''' (Morton), '''Kooky Von Koopa''' (Ludwig), '''Cheatsy Koopa''' (Larry), '''Kootie Pie Koopa''' (Wendy), and '''Hip and Hop Koopa''' (Lemmy and Iggy respectively). After this, they appear in another animated cartoon series ''[[Super Mario World (TV series)|Super Mario World]]'' with the same names, though they more closely resemble their portrayals in the video games. Aside from their names and personalities, they look slightly different and serve their father King Koopa (as Bowser was called in the series) differently compared to their video game counterparts. Instead of their subordinate role, they act directly as his children, and do things such as seek his attention, and even plot against him. They would also appear in the [[Nintendo Adventure Books]] and comic books, wherein they use their official names and designs closer to the games.{{cn|date=September 2017}}\n{{br}}\n==Voice actors and namesakes==\nMost of the Koopalings were named after celebrities\u2014mainly famous musicians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/how-a-mario-character-was-named-after-motorheads-lemmy-1750180427|title=How A Mario Character Was Named After Motorhead's Lemmy|first=Patrick|last=Klepek}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Vintage Games: An Insider Look at the History of Grand Theft Auto, Super Mario, and the Most Influential Games of All Time|last1=Loguidice|first1=Bill|last2=Barton|first2=Matt|publisher=[[CRC Press]]|year=2012|isbn=9781136137587|page=282|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mKF5AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA326}}</ref> Each Koopaling has had four or five voice actors in different media.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2| Name !! rowspan=2|Amada Anime series (1989) !! rowspan=2|DiC animated series (1990\u20131991) !! rowspan=2|''[[Mario Is Missing!]]'' (DOS, 1992) !! colspan=2|Video games (2009\u2013present) !! rowspan=2|Named after\n|-\n! <small>2009\u20132013,<br>2014\u20132019</small>{{refn|group=note|According to voice actor Mike Vaughn (Ludwig and Iggy), only one recording session was done in October of 2009 for ''New Super Mario Bros. Wii'', and those same audio files have been reused in several future titles that have featured the Koopalings since, the most recent being ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U|New Super Mario Bros. U Deluxe]]''. Vaughn has publicly called this action a theft by Nintendo as the usage release signed by both parties prohibited Nintendo from using those files in advertisements or promotions. While not specifically restricting usage in future games, Vaughn asked, \"Who in their right mind would have thought that a major game producer would use the same audio in future titles? Seems like a great way to make really bad, repetitive games to me.\"<ref>[http://www.blogtalkradio.com/cloverleafradio/2013/12/22/cloverleaf-radio-presents-actor-mike-vaughn-super-mario-bros Cloverleaf Radio Presents: Actor Mike Vaughn \"Super Mario Bros.\"!!]. Blog Talk Radio (January 2014). Retrieved November 18, 2014.</ref> Eventually, new voice actors were hired to record the Koopalings for ''Mario Kart 8'', with the exception of Roy, who retained his original voice actor.}} !! <small>2014\u2013present</small>\n|-\n| Larry Koopa || [[Masaharu Sat\u014d]] || James Rankin || Rob Wallace || rowspan=3|[[Lani Minella]] || Michelle Hippe || [[Larry Mullen Jr.|Larry Mullen]]\n|-\n| Morton Koopa Jr. || rowspan=2|[[Miyako End\u014d]] || Gordon Masten || {{N/a|Not used in final game}} || David Cooke || [[Morton Downey Jr.]]\n|-\n| Wendy O. Koopa || [[Tabitha St. Germain|Paulina Gillis]] || Kathy Fitzgerald || Ashley Flannegan || [[Wendy O. Williams]]\n|-\n| Iggy Koopa || Masaharu Sat\u014d || [[Tara Strong|Tara Charendoff]] || Rob Wallace || Mike Vaughn || Ryan Higgins || [[Iggy Pop]]\n|-\n| Roy Koopa || rowspan=3|[[Naoki Tatsuta]] || [[Dan Hennessey]]  || Bruce Sandig || colspan=2|Dan Falcone || [[Roy Orbison]]\n|-\n| Lemmy Koopa || Tara Charendoff || {{N/a|Not used in final game}} || Lani Minella || Carlee McManus || [[Lemmy|Lemmy Kilmister]]\n|-\n| Ludwig von Koopa || [[Michael Stark]] || Rob Wallace || Mike Vaughn || David J. Goldfarb || [[Ludwig van Beethoven]]\n|}\n\n==Reception==\nSince their appearance in ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'', the Koopalings have had mostly positive reception, being referred to by [[Nintendo]] as common knowledge of the ''Mario'' series due to their appearance in ''Super Mario Bros. 3''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ugo.com/games/super-mario-brothers-3-on-the-virtual-console |title=Super Mario Brothers 3 on the Virtual Console |publisher=UGO.com |date=November 5, 2007 |accessdate=August 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615033521/http://www.ugo.com/games/super-mario-brothers-3-on-the-virtual-console |archivedate=June 15, 2011  }}</ref> Their popularity amongst fans led to them being reused for the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]] sequel, ''[[Super Mario World]]''. [[Nintendo Power]] listed each Koopaling as one of the reasons to love Nintendo, describing them as some of Nintendo's most beloved villains. They cited their eccentric designs for the quality of their personalities.<ref>{{cite book |title=[[Nintendo Power]] 250th issue! |year=2010 |publisher=[[Future US]] |location=[[South San Francisco, California]] |page=60 }}</ref> The Koopalings were named the 19th best Mario villains by [[GameDaily]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Chris Buffa |url=http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/top-25-mario-enemies/?page=7&cp=2 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081207204712/http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/top-25-mario-enemies/?page=7&cp=2 |archivedate=December 7, 2008 |title=Gallery and Images |publisher=GameDaily |date=October 3, 2008 |accessdate=August 5, 2010}}</ref> [[GamesRadar]] editor Henry Gilbert described the battle at the end of each world in ''Super Mario Bros. 3'' as a \"special affair\"; he also praised them for adding variety to the series compared to ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'', which featured Bowser as the last boss of each castle.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/f/super-mario-bros-3-20-years-later/a-2010021210412332034/p-2/c-1?newest |title=Super Mario Bros 3: 20 years later |publisher=GamesRadar |accessdate=August 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615200618/http://www.gamesradar.com/f/super-mario-bros-3-20-years-later/a-2010021210412332034/p-2/c-1?newest |archivedate=June 15, 2011  }}</ref> [[IGN]] editor Lucas M. Thomas echoed these sentiments, stating that the Koopalings brought their own looks, mannerisms, and methods of attack. Specifically, he described the battle with Lemmy Koopa in ''Super Mario Bros. 3'' as unique and memorable, while also describing Ludwig von Koopa's battle in ''[[Super Mario World]]'' as distinct from the others.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thomas |first=Lucas M. |url=http://stars.ign.com/articles/998/998186p1.html |title=Revenge of the Koopalings: Stars Icons \u2013 Stars Feature at IGN |publisher=Stars.ign.com |date=June 29, 2009 |accessdate=August 5, 2010}}</ref> In another article he listed the Koopalings as one of the characters he wants in ''[[Mario Kart 7]]'', especially Wendy O. Koopa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.ds.ign.com/articles/121/1213061p1.html|title=Predicting Mario Kart 7's Final Characters|publisher=IGN|first=Lucas M.|last=Thomas|accessdate=September 18, 2016 }}</ref> Fellow IGN editor Jesse Schedeen featured the Koopalings in the \"Big Boss of the Day\" feature, describing them as popular bosses in video games.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schedeen |first=Jesse |url=http://stars.ign.com/articles/105/1052937p1.html |title=Big Boss of the Day: The Koopa Kids \u2013 Stars Feature at IGN |publisher=Stars.ign.com |date=December 7, 2009 |accessdate=August 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Joystiq]] editor James Ransom-Wiley called their reappearance in ''[[New Super Mario Bros. Wii]]'' a welcome addition, stating that it should boost the quality of the bosses.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ransom |first=James |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2006/03/09/koopalings-to-return-in-new-super-mario-bros-yoshi-on-the-side/ |title=Koopalings to return in New Super Mario Bros., Yoshi on the sideline |publisher=Joystiq |date=March 9, 2006 |accessdate=August 5, 2010}}</ref> Fellow Joystiq editor JC Fletcher described them as a draw for ''New Super Mario Bros. Wii'' for some fans, also praising the three-dimensional designs of the Koopalings.<ref>{{cite web|author=JC Fletcher on |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2009/10/26/new-super-character-art-from-new-super-mario-bros-wii/ |title=New, super character art from New Super Mario Bros. Wii |publisher=Joystiq |date=October 26, 2009 |accessdate=August 5, 2010}}</ref> During an interview with ''[[Super Mario Galaxy]]'' director [[Yoshiaki Koizumi]], [[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] noted that they were hoping for the Koopalings to return in it.<ref name=\"egm\">{{cite web |url=http://www.1up.com/features/super-mario-galaxy-afterthoughts |title=Super Mario Galaxy Afterthoughts from |publisher=1UP.com |date=February 19, 2008 |accessdate=August 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111129052432/http://www.1up.com/features/super-mario-galaxy-afterthoughts |archivedate=November 29, 2011  }}</ref> [[Destructoid]] editor Conrad Zimmerman stated that the Koopalings were his favorite characters from ''Super Mario Bros. 3'', and added that with regard to the musical references in the Koopalings' names, he doubted that anything similar would be seen in this day and age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/see-larry-koopa-strut-his-stuff-once-more-137093.phtml |title=See Larry Koopa strut his stuff once more |publisher=Destructoid |accessdate=August 5, 2010}}</ref> [[GameSpy]] editor Ryan Scott listed the Koopalings as one of the reasons why ''Super Mario Bros. 3'' and ''Super Mario World'' were quality video games.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespy.com/articles/105/1057201p2.html |title=Game of the Year 2009: Our Personal Picks \u2013 Page 2 |publisher=GameSpy |accessdate=August 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226020637/http://www.gamespy.com/articles/105/1057201p2.html |archivedate=December 26, 2009  }}</ref> He also praised ''New Super Mario Bros. Wii'' for the inclusion of the Koopalings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wii.gamespy.com/wii/super-mario-wii-2/991378p1.html |title=GameSpy: E3 2009: New Super Mario Bros. Wii Hands-on \u2013 Page 1 |publisher=Wii.gamespy.com |accessdate=August 5, 2010}}</ref> The GameSpy staff listed the Koopalings as some of their favorite bosses, stating that they have much more charm than their \"dopey successor\", Bowser Jr.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://xbox360.gamespy.com/articles/103/1036217p1.html |title=GameSpy: GameSpy's Favorite Videogame Bosses \u2013 Page 1 |publisher=Xbox360.gamespy.com |accessdate=August 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808171233/http://xbox360.gamespy.com/articles/103/1036217p1.html |archivedate=August 8, 2010  }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Wikipedia books|Mario franchise characters}}\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Mario franchise}}\n{{Super Smash Bros. series}}\n\n[[Category:Anthropomorphic characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Child characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional criminals in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional kidnappers]]\n[[Category:Fictional turtles]]\n[[Category:Mario enemies]]\n[[Category:Super Smash Bros. fighters]]\n[[Category:Mario characters]]\n[[Category:Nintendo antagonists]]\n[[Category:Fictional septets]]\n[[Category:Video game bosses]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 1988]]\n[[Category:Video game nobility]]\n[[Category:Fictional henchmen in video games]]\n[[Category:Video game characters who use magic]]\n[[Category:Video game characters with fire or heat abilities]]\n", "name_user": "SmashStar30", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSuper Mario series:Six if you count SMM2!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Koopalings"}
{"title_page": "Kristiansand Cathedral", "text_new": "{{Infobox church\n|name                   = Kristiansand Cathedral\n|fullname               = Kristiansand domkirke\n|image                  = File:Kristiansand Church.jpg\n|imagesize              = \n|imagealt               = \n|caption                = View of the cathedral\n|pushpin map            = Vest-Agder#Norway\n|pushpin label position = left\n|pushpin mapsize        = \n|map caption            = Location of the church\n|coordinates            = {{coord|58.1461|07.9947|region:NO_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|location               = [[Kristiansand]], [[Vest-Agder]]\n|country                = [[Norway]]\n|denomination           = [[Church of Norway]]\n|churchmanship          = [[Evangelical Lutheran]]\n|website                = [http://www.kristiansanddomkirke.no/ www.kristiansanddomkirke.no]\n|former name            = Trinity Church,<br /> Our Saviors Church\n|founded date           = \n|consecrated date       = 18 Mar 1885\n|completed date         = 1 Feb 1885\n|events                 = \n|status                 = [[Cathedral]]\n|functional status      = Active\n|architect              = [[Henrik Thrap-Meyer]]\n|architectural type     = \n|style                  = [[Neo-Gothic]], [[Cruciform]]\n|materials              = Brick, cement\n|closed date            = \n|capacity               = 1,000\n|parish                 = Kristiansand domkirken\n|deanery                = [[Kristiansand prosti]] \n|diocese                = [[Diocese of Agder og Telemark|Agder og Telemark]]\n|bishop                 = \n|dean                   = \n}} \n\n'''Kristiansand Cathedral''' ({{lang-no|Kristiansand domkirke}}) is a [[cathedral]] in [[Kristiansand]] municipality in [[Vest-Agder]] county, [[Norway]]. It is located in the [[Kvadraturen (Kristiansand)|Kvadraturen]] area in the central part of the city of [[Kristiansand]]. The church is the main church for the Kristiansand domkirken [[parish]] and it is the seat of the [[Kristiansand prosti|Kristiansand]] arch-[[deanery]] within the [[Diocese of Agder og Telemark]]. The cathedral is also the seat of the [[Bishop of Agder and Telemark]].  The brick church was completed in 1885 and is one of the largest cathedrals in Norway. This cathedral is the fourth church and third cathedral to be located on this site over the centuries.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kirkesok.no/eng/kirker/Kristiansand-domkirke|title=Kristiansand domkirke|publisher=Kirkes\u00f8k: Kirkebyggdatabasen|accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kirkekonsulenten.no/kirker.htm|title=Oversikt over N\u00e5v\u00e6rende Kirker|language=Norwegian|publisher=KirkeKonsulenten.no |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref><ref name=\"KB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kristiansanddomkirke.no/kirkebygget.html|title=Kirkebygget|publisher=Kristiansand kirkelige fellesr\u00e5d|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nKristiansand Cathedral is a [[Neo-Gothic]] church built of brick and cement, of [[cruciform]] plan with 1,750 seats. The church was designed by the architect [[Henrik Thrap-Meyer]]. Construction began in 1880 and was completed on 1 February 1885. The church was [[consecrate]]d on 18 March 1885 by the provost Johan M. Brun who was serving as acting bishop.<ref name=\"KB\" /><ref name=\"nbl\">{{cite web|url=https://nbl.snl.no/Henrik_Thrap-Meyer|title=Henrik Thrap-Meyer|author=Norsk biografisk leksikon|authorlink=Norsk biografisk leksikon|editor-last=Indahl|editor-first=Trond|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>\n\nThe cathedral is {{convert|60|m}} long and {{convert|38.7|m}} wide.  The [[steeple]] is {{convert|70|m|ft}} in height. Originally the cathedral had 2,029&nbsp;seats and room for an additional 1,216 people to stand, but seating has now been reduced so the building can comfortably seat about 1,000. To re-use the walls of the previous cathedral, which burned down in 1880, the [[altar]] was positioned at the west end, rather than in the traditional position in the east.<ref name=\"KB\" />\n\nThe cathedral received a [[carillon]] with 36 bells as a gift from [[Glencore|Falconbridge Nikkelverk]] in 1990, created by [[Olsen Nauen Bell Foundry]].<ref name=hist>[http://www.kristiansanddomkirke.no/aringpen-kirke.html Kristiansand Domkirke \u2013 en kort historisk beskrivelse] from the Official Website {{in lang|no}}</ref>\n\nKristiansand Cathedral received a new [[church organ]], built by the German supplier Klais in 2013, comprising a 58-voice main organ at the eastern balcony and another of 9 voices at the northern balcony.<ref name=\"hist\" />\n\n==History==\nThe cathedral is in the same location as three previous buildings. The first, called {{lang|no|Trefoldigetskirken}} (Trinity Church), a small wooden church, was built in 1645. When Kristiansand was appointed the seat of the diocese in 1682, construction began on the town's first cathedral, called {{lang|no|Vor Frelsers Kirke}} (Our Saviour's Church). That first cathedral, built in stone, was consecrated in 1696, but burned down in 1734. The second cathedral, consecrated in 1738, was destroyed by a fire that affected the whole city, on 18&nbsp;December 1880. This church has been reconstructed and rebuilt in size 1:10. The model is on display at the [[Vest-Agder Museum Kristiansand]]. It was built by a group of enthusiastic model builders.\n\nThe current cathedral, which is larger than its predecessor, was consecrated in 1885. When the 1940 [[Nazi Germany|Nazi]] [[Norwegian Campaign|attack on Kristiansand]] took place early in the morning of 9&nbsp;April 1940, the {{convert|70|m|adj=on}}-tall cathedral tower was hit by an [[artillery shell]], which damaged the upper part.<ref>{{cite web|first=Flemming|last=Jensen|url=http://www.agderkultur.no/Kristiansand%20domkirke/Side1.htm|title=Domkirkens historie|publisher=AgderKultur.no|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2017-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110211162053/http://www.agderkultur.no/Kristiansand%20domkirke/Side1.htm|archive-date=2011-02-11|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agderkultur.no/Kirkerommet/Side%201.htm|title=Kristiansand domkirke Kirkerommet|publisher=Vest-Agder Fylkesmuseum|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2017-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426052124/http://www.agderkultur.no/Kirkerommet/Side%201.htm|archive-date=2012-04-26|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"180px\" mode=packed>\nFile:Kristiansand domkyrkje interioer 2.jpg|Interior\nFile:Kristiansand domkyrkje orgelet..jpg|Organ  \nFile:Kristiansand domkyrkje preikestol.jpg|Pulpit \nFile:Kristiansand Domkirke - Inne.jpg|Sanctuary\nFile:Kristiansand domkirke, Vest-Agder - Riksantikvaren-T150 01 0346.jpg|The previous Kristiansand Cathedral, built 1738, burned down 1880<br>(<small>Image:[[Norwegian Directorate for Cultural Heritage]])</small>\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of cathedrals in Norway]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Kristiansand domkirke}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.kristiansanddomkirke.no/index.html}} {{in lang|no}}\n*{{Official website|http://kristiansandcathedral.weebly.com/}} {{in lang|en}}\n*[https://roundme.com/tour/33846/view/82230/ Virtual Interior Kristiansand Cathedral, 360\u00b0 Panorama (New church organs)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hzlsHceN8gc View from the Church Tower] VIDEO\n\n{{Cathedrals of Norway}}\n{{Churches in Kristiansand}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Kristiansand|Cathedral]]\n[[Category:Churches in Kristiansand]]\n[[Category:Churches in Vest-Agder]]\n[[Category:Cathedrals in Norway]]\n[[Category:Lutheran cathedrals in Norway]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1885]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Kristiansand]]\n[[Category:Cruciform churches in Norway]]\n[[Category:1645 establishments in Norway]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox church\n|name                   = Kristiansand Cathedral\n|fullname               = Kristiansand domkirke\n|image                  = File:Kristiansand Church.jpg\n|imagesize              = \n|imagealt               = \n|caption                = View of the cathedral\n|pushpin map            = Vest-Agder#Norway\n|pushpin label position = left\n|pushpin mapsize        = \n|map caption            = Location of the church\n|coordinates            = {{coord|58.1461|07.9947|region:NO_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|location               = [[Kristiansand]], [[Vest-Agder]]\n|country                = [[Norway]]\n|denomination           = [[Church of Norway]]\n|churchmanship          = [[Evangelical Lutheran]]\n|website                = [http://www.kristiansanddomkirke.no/ www.kristiansanddomkirke.no]\n|former name            = Trinity Church,<br /> Our Saviors Church\n|founded date           = \n|consecrated date       = 18 Mar 1885\n|completed date         = 1 Feb 1885\n|events                 = \n|status                 = [[Cathedral]]\n|functional status      = Active\n|architect              = [[Henrik Thrap-Meyer]]\n|architectural type     = \n|style                  = [[Neo-Gothic]], [[Cruciform]]\n|materials              = Brick, cement\n|closed date            = \n|capacity               = 1,000\n|parish                 = Kristiansand domkirken\n|deanery                = [[Kristiansand prosti]] \n|diocese                = [[Diocese of Agder og Telemark|Agder og Telemark]]\n|bishop                 = \n|dean                   = \n}} \n\n'''Kristiansand Cathedral''' ({{lang-no|Kristiansand domkirke}}) is a [[cathedral]] in [[Kristiansand]] municipality in [[Vest-Agder]] county, [[Norway]]. It is located in the [[Kvadraturen (Kristiansand)|Kvadraturen]] area in the central part of the city of [[Kristiansand]]. The church is the main church for the Kristiansand domkirken [[parish]] and it is the seat of the [[Kristiansand prosti|Kristiansand]] arch-[[deanery]] within the [[Diocese of Agder og Telemark]]. The cathedral is also the seat of the [[Bishop of Agder and Telemark]].  The brick church was completed in 1885 and is one of the largest cathedrals in Norway. This cathedral is the fourth church and third cathedral to be located on this site over the centuries.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kirkesok.no/eng/kirker/Kristiansand-domkirke|title=Kristiansand domkirke|publisher=Kirkes\u00f8k: Kirkebyggdatabasen|accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kirkekonsulenten.no/kirker.htm|title=Oversikt over N\u00e5v\u00e6rende Kirker|language=Norwegian|publisher=KirkeKonsulenten.no |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref><ref name=\"KB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kristiansanddomkirke.no/kirkebygget.html|title=Kirkebygget|publisher=Kristiansand kirkelige fellesr\u00e5d|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nKristiansand Cathedral is a [[Neo-Gothic]] church built of brick and cement, of [[cruciform]] plan with 1,750 seats. The church was designed by the architect [[Henrik Thrap-Meyer]]. Construction began in 1880 and was completed on 1 February 1885. The church was [[consecrate]]d on 18 March 1885 by the provost Johan M. Brun who was serving as acting bishop.<ref name=\"KB\" /><ref name=\"nbl\">{{cite web|url=https://nbl.snl.no/Henrik_Thrap-Meyer|title=Henrik Thrap-Meyer|author=Norsk biografisk leksikon|authorlink=Norsk biografisk leksikon|editor-last=Indahl|editor-first=Trond|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>\n\nThe cathedral is {{convert|60|m}} long and {{convert|38.7|m}} wide.  The [[steeple]] is {{convert|70|m|ft}} in height. Originally the cathedral had 2,029&nbsp;seats and room for an additional 1,216 people to stand, but seating has now been reduced so the building can comfortably seat about 1,000. To re-use the walls of the previous cathedral, which burned down in 1880, the [[altar]] was positioned at the west end, rather than in the traditional position in the east.<ref name=\"KB\" />\n\nThe cathedral received a [[carillon]] with 36 bells as a gift from [[Glencore|Falconbridge Nikkelverk]] in 1990, created by [[Olsen Nauen Bell Foundry]].<ref name=hist>[http://www.kristiansanddomkirke.no/aringpen-kirke.html Kristiansand Domkirke \u2013 en kort historisk beskrivelse] from the Official Website {{in lang|no}}</ref>\n\nKristiansand Cathedral received a new [[church organ]], built by the German supplier Klais in 2013, comprising a 58-voice main organ at the eastern balcony and another of 9 voices at the northern balcony.<ref name=\"hist\" />\n\n==History==\nThe cathedral is in the same location as three previous buildings. The first, called {{lang|no|Trefoldigetskirken}} (Trinity Church), a small wooden church, was built in 1645. When Kristiansand was appointed the seat of the diocese in 1682, construction began on the town's first cathedral, called {{lang|no|Vor Frelsers Kirke}} (Our Saviour's Church). That first cathedral, built in stone, was consecrated in 1696, but burned down in 1734. The second cathedral, consecrated in 1738, was destroyed by a fire that affected the whole city, on 18&nbsp;December 1880. This church has been reconstructed and rebuilt in size 1:10. The model is on display at the [[Vest-Agder Museum Kristiansand]]. It was rebuilt built by a group of enthusiastic model builders.\n\nThe current cathedral, which is larger than its predecessor, was consecrated in 1885. When the 1940 [[Nazi Germany|Nazi]] [[Norwegian Campaign|attack on Kristiansand]] took place early in the morning of 9&nbsp;April 1940, the {{convert|70|m|adj=on}}-tall cathedral tower was hit by an [[artillery shell]], which damaged the upper part.<ref>{{cite web|first=Flemming|last=Jensen|url=http://www.agderkultur.no/Kristiansand%20domkirke/Side1.htm|title=Domkirkens historie|publisher=AgderKultur.no|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2017-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110211162053/http://www.agderkultur.no/Kristiansand%20domkirke/Side1.htm|archive-date=2011-02-11|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agderkultur.no/Kirkerommet/Side%201.htm|title=Kristiansand domkirke Kirkerommet|publisher=Vest-Agder Fylkesmuseum|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2017-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426052124/http://www.agderkultur.no/Kirkerommet/Side%201.htm|archive-date=2012-04-26|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"180px\" mode=packed>\nFile:Kristiansand domkyrkje interioer 2.jpg|Interior\nFile:Kristiansand domkyrkje orgelet..jpg|Organ  \nFile:Kristiansand domkyrkje preikestol.jpg|Pulpit \nFile:Kristiansand Domkirke - Inne.jpg|Sanctuary\nFile:Kristiansand domkirke, Vest-Agder - Riksantikvaren-T150 01 0346.jpg|The previous Kristiansand Cathedral, built 1738, burned down 1880<br>(<small>Image:[[Norwegian Directorate for Cultural Heritage]])</small>\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of cathedrals in Norway]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Kristiansand domkirke}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.kristiansanddomkirke.no/index.html}} {{in lang|no}}\n*{{Official website|http://kristiansandcathedral.weebly.com/}} {{in lang|en}}\n*[https://roundme.com/tour/33846/view/82230/ Virtual Interior Kristiansand Cathedral, 360\u00b0 Panorama (New church organs)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hzlsHceN8gc View from the Church Tower] VIDEO\n\n{{Cathedrals of Norway}}\n{{Churches in Kristiansand}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Kristiansand|Cathedral]]\n[[Category:Churches in Kristiansand]]\n[[Category:Churches in Vest-Agder]]\n[[Category:Cathedrals in Norway]]\n[[Category:Lutheran cathedrals in Norway]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1885]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Kristiansand]]\n[[Category:Cruciform churches in Norway]]\n[[Category:1645 establishments in Norway]]\n", "name_user": "Carsten R D", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kristiansand_Cathedral"}
