enth Avenue Line | service=Broadway-Seventh north local}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|alltimes}}\n| embedded = <hr>{{Infobox NRHP\n  | embed = yes\n  | added = September 15, 1983\n  | name = IRT Broadway Line Viaduct (a.k.a.; Manhattan Valley Viaduct)\n  | refnum = 83001749<ref name=\"focus\">{{Cite archive|collection=Records of the National Park Service, 1785 - 2006|institution=National Archives|item-url=https://catalog.archives.gov/id/75319648|series=National Register of Historic Places and National Historic Landmarks Program Records, 2013 - 2017|item=New York SP IRT Broadway Line Viaduct|item-id=75319648 |box=National Register of Historic Places and National Historic Landmarks Program Records: New York}}</ref>\n| designated_other2 = NYC Landmark\n| designated_other2_date = November 24, 1981<ref name=\"NYCL-1094\"/>\n| designated_other2_number = 1094\n| designated_other2_abbr = NYCL\n| designated_other2_color = #FFE978\n| designated_other2_link = New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''125th Street''' (formerly '''Manhattan Street''') is a local [[metro station|station]] on the [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. Located at the intersection of [[125th Street (Manhattan)|125th Street]] and [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]], at the border of the [[Manhattanville, Manhattan|Manhattanville]] and [[Morningside Heights, Manhattan|Morningside Heights]] neighborhoods of [[Manhattan]], it is served by the [[1 (New York City Subway service)|1]] train at all times.\n\n== History ==\n{{Stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 3-tracked local station\n|1=137th Street\u2013City College\n|l1=137 St\n|2=116th Street\u2013Columbia University\n|l2=116 St\n|code=IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line\n|color=Seventh\n|unused=yes\n|deg=330\n}}\n}}\nOperation of the [[Early history of the IRT subway|first subway]] began on October 27, 1904, with the opening of the original 28 stations of the New York City Subway from [[City Hall (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)|City Hall]] to [[145th Street (IRT Broadway \u2013 Seventh Avenue Line)|145th Street]] on the West Side Branch including the 125th Street station.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/fiftyyearsrapid00walkgoog|title=Fifty Years of Rapid Transit \u2014 1864 to 1917|last1=Walker|first1=James Blaine|date=1918|publisher=Law Printing|isbn=|location=New York, N.Y.|pages=|accessdate=November 6, 2016}}</ref>{{Rp|162\u2013191}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1904/10/27/101400669.pdf|title=Subway Opening To-day With Simple Ceremony \u2013 Exercises at One O'Clock \u2013 Public to be Admitted at Seven \u2013 John Hay May Be Present \u2013 Expected to Represent the Federal Government \u2013 President Roosevelt Sends Letter of Regret|last=|first=|date=October 27, 1904|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 28, 2017|archive-url=|archive-date=|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, platforms on the [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]] from 103rd Street to 238th Street were lengthened to {{Convert|514|feet|meters|abbr=}} to allow full ten-car trains to platform. Previously the stations could only platform six-car trains. The platform extensions were opened in stages. The platform extensions at 125th Street opened on June 11, 1948.<ref name=\"BOT-19492\">{{Cite book|title=Report for the three and one-half years ending June 30, 1949.|date=1949|publisher=New York City Board of Transportation|hdl = 2027/mdp.39015023094926}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1948/07/10/86748393.pdf|title=More Long Platforms \u2013 Five Subway Stations on IRT to Accommodate 10-Car Trains|date=July 10, 1948|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=March 27, 2016|url-status=live|page=8|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, it was announced that 125th Street would be one of ten subway stations citywide, as well as one of five on the IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line, to receive renovations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/boroughs/renovation-set-10-subway-stations-article-1.485558|title=Renovation Is Set For 10 Subway Stations|last=|first=|date=June 11, 2002|work=New York Daily News|access-date=January 8, 2018|archive-url=|archive-date=|language=en}}</ref> The renovation took place the following year.\n\n== Station layout ==\n{{NYCS Platform Layout IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line/local/3 tracks/elevated}}\n[[File:BwyWalk0505 Station125thBroadway.jpg|thumb|left|220px|The station seen up close from Broadway.]]\nThis station was part of the original subway. It has two [[side platform]]s and three tracks; the center track is not used in revenue service.<ref name=\"tracks\">{{NYCS const|trackref|trackbook3}}</ref> Both platforms have beige windscreens and red canopies with windows and green frames and outlines in the center that were installed in a 2003 renovation. On either side, there are green, waist-high, ironwork fences.\n\nThe 125th Street station is the only station on the {{convert|2174|ft|m|-long|abbr=|adj=mid}} Manhattan Valley Viaduct, which bridges [[Manhattanville]] from 122nd to 135th Streets and has been on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] since 1983.<ref name=\"focus\" /> The viaduct allows the trains to remain relatively level and avoid steep grades while traversing the valley. The steel arch across 125th Street is {{convert|168.5|ft|m}} long and {{Convert|54|ft||abbr=}} high. Most of the remainder of the viaduct is a simple steel structure, similar to other early IRT lines, except the approach ramps from 122nd to LaSalle Streets and from 133rd to 135th Streets, which are made of masonry.<ref>{{cite book |title=Guide to Civil Engineering Projects In and Around New York City |edition=2nd |publisher=Metropolitan Section, American Society of Civil Engineers |year=2009 |pages=90\u201391}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL-1094\">{{cite report|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1094.pdf|title=Interborough Rapid Transit System, Manhattan Valley Viaduct|last=Framberger|first=David|last2=Sklar|first2=Barbara|date=November 24, 1981|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|pages=3|access-date=November 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226173938/http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1094.pdf|archive-date=December 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n===Exits===\nThis station has one elevated station house at the center of the platforms and tracks. Two staircases from each side go down to a waiting area/crossunder, where a [[turnstile]] bank provides access to and from the station. Outside [[fare control]], there is a token booth and an enclosed passageway on the west side leading to two escalators going down to the west side of Broadway, diverging in opposite directions. One escalator leads to 125th Street while the other leads to Tiemann Place. On the east side of the station house, another enclosed passageway leads to an escalator facing south and going down to the southeast corner of Broadway and 125th Street. Adjacent to this passageway is an \"L\" shaped staircase with its upper half directly above Broadway and the lower half beneath the enclosed escalator going to the same corner of the intersection.<ref>{{Cite NYC neighborhood map|Morningside Heights}}</ref>\n\n== Image gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:BwyWalk0505 Station125thBroadway2.jpg|The tracks leading south to the station, which is visible behind (south of) the northbound {{NYCS|1}} train.\nFile:125th Street Subway control area 1978.jpg|The station's entrance and turnstiles in 1978.\nFile:125th Street Escalator.jpg|Staircase and passageway to escalator.\nFile:1 trains at 125th Street .jpg|thumb|Two 1 trains at 125th Street station showing much of Broadway past the portal at 135th Street in the distance. Seen from the 122nd Street portal. \nFile:135thStreetPortalViewHDR.jpg|An [[High-dynamic-range imaging|HDRI]] photo from the 135th Street portal, facing south on Broadway.\nFile:122ndStreetPortal1train.jpg|A northbound 1 train approaching the 125th Street station, as seen from the 122nd Street portal.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category multi|125th Street (IRT Broadway \u2013 Seventh Avenue Line)|Manhattan Valley Viaduct}} \n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?6:3143|IRT West Side Line|125th Street}}\n* nycsubway.org \u2013 [http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/artwork_show?70 River to River Artwork by Wopo Holup (1991)]\n* Station Reporter \u2013 [https://web.archive.org/web/20141010102251/http://www.stationreporter.net/1train.htm 1 Train]\n* Forgotten NY \u2013 [http://forgotten-ny.com/2006/01/the-original-28-part-2-a-look-at-the-artwork-from-the-nycs-first-28-stations-opened-october-27-1904/ Original 28 - NYC's First 28 Subway Stations] \n* The Subway Nut \u2013 [http://www.subwaynut.com/irt/125n1/index.php  125th Street Pictures]\n* [https://maps.google.com/maps?ie=UTF8&ll=40.815734,-73.958459&spn=0.003816,0.013433&z=17&layer=c&cbll=40.815833,-73.958397&panoid=tYYlX-UzbB5hwpH7eOdo9Q&cbp=12,231.96,,0,-2.62 125th Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://maps.google.com/maps?ie=UTF8&ll=40.815766,-73.958437&spn=0.003816,0.013433&z=17&layer=c&cbll=40.815181,-73.958861&panoid=0mFtpL1bTgv8_Lifn3JXVg&cbp=12,354.74,,0,5.65 Tiemann Place entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://maps.google.com/maps?hl=en&ll=40.815084,-73.958824&spn=0.002972,0.009645&t=m&z=17&layer=c&cbll=40.81508,-73.958827&panoid=CGy3YJIifJUAAAAAAABkNA&cbp=12,53.75,,0,-6.61 Platforms from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|l1=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|7ave=yes}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n{{NRHP bridges}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:125th Street (Irt Broadway-Seventh Avenue Line)}}\n[[Category:IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:Broadway (Manhattan)]]\n[[Category:Railroad bridges on the Na